0,"is_bookmarked":0,"can_be_copied":1,"can_remove_fork":1,"forks_count":{"private":0,"public":0},"access":{"can_view":1,"can_remove":0,"can_add":1,"can_edit":0,"can_publish":0,"can_get_doi":0,"can_share":1,"can_move":1,"can_move_outside":1,"can_transfer":1,"can_download":1,"is_locked":0},"guid":"03AB2677E6F341E1A7456FEFC819AB14","steps":[{"id":828609,"guid":"3546363148E540839C53D21028EF0B59","previous_id":null,"previous_guid":null,"modified_on":0,"protocol_id":0,"components":[{"id":1054723,"guid":"D5DB35758D3941C1A7F29E83D1CDCF3E","order_id":1,"type_id":6,"title":"Section","source":{"title":""}},{"id":1054724,"guid":"EBDFC61EAC1C4CD690165831E9120BA3","order_id":1,"type_id":1,"title":"description","source":{"description":"<div class = \"text-blocks\"><div class = \"text-block\"><span>Perfusion fix mouse or rat kidneys with 2% paraformaldehyde or PLP. Embed in paraffin. Cut 3 and 9 um thick sections longitudinally through each kidney (<\/span><span style = \"font-weight:bold;\">See Vascular Perfusion Protocol<\/span><span>). It is important to initially establish the actual section thickness generated by each cryotome since this can vary substantially.<\/span><\/div><\/div>"}}],"cases":[],"data":null,"section":null,"section_color":null,"critical":null,"critical_id":null,"duration":0},{"id":828610,"guid":"1ABEBE5BD0D142D780B2ED662C0B408F","previous_id":828609,"previous_guid":"3546363148E540839C53D21028EF0B59","modified_on":0,"protocol_id":0,"components":[{"id":1054723,"guid":"9F72510AAFAF45A3B50C840C8C615BDF","order_id":1,"type_id":6,"title":"Section","source":{"title":""}},{"id":1054724,"guid":"AB9B687DAEA64B098BA4E65B732914D5","order_id":1,"type_id":1,"title":"description","source":{"description":"<div class = \"text-blocks\"><div class = \"text-block\"><span>Stain sections with WT-1 antibody and immunoperoxidase usingconventional immunohistochemical procedures and solutions (<\/span><span style = \"font-weight:bold;\">See WT-1 Staining Protocol for podocytes for details<\/span><span>).<\/span><\/div><\/div>"}}],"cases":[],"data":null,"section":null,"section_color":null,"critical":null,"critical_id":null,"duration":0},{"id":828611,"guid":"0BAAA5DC54C5466C9274D73C8065B3F7","previous_id":828610,"previous_guid":"1ABEBE5BD0D142D780B2ED662C0B408F","modified_on":0,"protocol_id":0,"components":[{"id":1054723,"guid":"DCB7E2B975614105AD4DF414082DD4AB","order_id":1,"type_id":6,"title":"Section","source":{"title":""}},{"id":1054724,"guid":"11736EAED26B4A8A902567BBB19D096C","order_id":1,"type_id":1,"title":"description","source":{"description":"<div class = \"text-blocks\"><div class = \"text-block\">Take photo graphs of entire cortical area at 40x power using a Spot Advanced Software or similar camera.<\/div><\/div>"}}],"cases":[],"data":null,"section":null,"section_color":null,"critical":null,"critical_id":null,"duration":0},{"id":828612,"guid":"0322A32E8323449FB676CEB05962B027","previous_id":828611,"previous_guid":"0BAAA5DC54C5466C9274D73C8065B3F7","modified_on":0,"protocol_id":0,"components":[{"id":1054723,"guid":"314C5AD545D34F2AB421641F82A18656","order_id":1,"type_id":6,"title":"Section","source":{"title":""}},{"id":1054724,"guid":"3C7E2C275D624538B73619252403A22F","order_id":1,"type_id":1,"title":"description","source":{"description":"<div class = \"text-blocks\"><div class = \"text-block\">Photograph 50 consecutive glomerular cross-sections per animal, moving systematically from outer cortex to inner cortex and back again across the slide to ensure equivalent sampling from all cortical regions. Use phase contrast to capture images as this renders WT-1 stained podocyte nuclei a bright golden color that makes them easier to detect.<\/div><\/div>"}}],"cases":[],"data":null,"section":null,"section_color":null,"critical":null,"critical_id":null,"duration":0},{"id":828613,"guid":"18373AB2682743CDB9B8F1DC3338D0DC","previous_id":828612,"previous_guid":"0322A32E8323449FB676CEB05962B027","modified_on":0,"protocol_id":0,"components":[{"id":1054723,"guid":"D802AE8C5D09432F984048702051CD72","order_id":1,"type_id":6,"title":"Section","source":{"title":""}},{"id":1054724,"guid":"E059070730534792A593B8DC3C46D017","order_id":1,"type_id":1,"title":"description","source":{"description":"<div class = \"text-blocks\"><div class = \"text-block\">From these photo micrographs (approximately 30\/slide), measure the glomerular area (see step #6) by using Metamorph Image Analysis Software and count the podocytes in 50 sequential glomerular cross-sections at two thicknesses (3 and 9 microns).<\/div><\/div>"}}],"cases":[],"data":null,"section":null,"section_color":null,"critical":null,"critical_id":null,"duration":0},{"id":828614,"guid":"408AF24C8A5140648161B89F0E7D59B4","previous_id":828613,"previous_guid":"18373AB2682743CDB9B8F1DC3338D0DC","modified_on":0,"protocol_id":0,"components":[{"id":1054723,"guid":"E7D6D9E19A5A423FBF47236CC76CB078","order_id":1,"type_id":6,"title":"Section","source":{"title":""}},{"id":1054724,"guid":"FBE38EA3C61544CEBBB2BE05B397A1F0","order_id":1,"type_id":1,"title":"description","source":{"description":"<div class = \"text-blocks\"><div class = \"text-block\"><span>To measure the glomerular area using Metamorph software, camera and microscope should be calibrated and values should be loaded into Metamorph program before outlining the glomerular tuft area. Click on the desktop icon (Metamorph software icon) to open the Metamorph program, and then open the images. From the menu bar, select <\/span><span style = \"font-weight:bold;\">Measure<\/span><span>, then select <\/span><span style = \"font-weight:bold;\">Calibrate Distance<\/span><span>. A calibration window will appear. Highlight the <\/span><span style = \"font-weight:bold;\">40x<\/span><span> calibration and then click <\/span><span style = \"font-weight:bold;\">Apply<\/span><span>. Use <\/span><span style = \"font-weight:bold;\">Polygon tool<\/span><span> from menu bar for outlining the glomerular tuft area. From the menu bar, select <\/span><span style = \"font-weight:bold;\">Measure<\/span><span> and then <\/span><span style = \"font-weight:bold;\">Region Measurement<\/span><span> to obtain the measurement of the glomerular tuft area.<\/span><\/div><\/div>"}}],"cases":[],"data":null,"section":null,"section_color":null,"critical":null,"critical_id":null,"duration":0},{"id":828615,"guid":"1B07F5C8EB894820842F6A526D814BF9","previous_id":828614,"previous_guid":"408AF24C8A5140648161B89F0E7D59B4","modified_on":0,"protocol_id":0,"components":[{"id":1054723,"guid":"027BC37AE2F140399A88003D17C3112C","order_id":1,"type_id":6,"title":"Section","source":{"title":""}},{"id":1054724,"guid":"BB8AFFD92EE642CEA9B33AE087A9218B","order_id":1,"type_id":1,"title":"description","source":{"description":"<div class = \"text-blocks\"><div class = \"text-block\"><span>Some artifacts can appear to be WT-1 positive, but these are usually smaller than podocyte nuclei. To make certain that a reasonable and consistent size cut-off is used to correctly identify podocyte nuclei, choose <\/span><span style = \"font-weight:bold;\">Measure<\/span><span> from the menu bar then choose<\/span><span style = \"font-weight:bold;\"> Manually Count Objects<\/span><span>. Select the number <\/span><span style = \"font-weight:bold;\">6<\/span><span>. Use this size restriction method to check if the number 6 from the Metamorph Image Analysis System fits within the nuclear profile. If so, count it. If the number 6 was larger than the WT-1 positive area, do not count it.<\/span><\/div><\/div>"}}],"cases":[],"data":null,"section":null,"section_color":null,"critical":null,"critical_id":null,"duration":0},{"id":828616,"guid":"9692FADAA4A54EF3981263C6E4E39A80","previous_id":828615,"previous_guid":"1B07F5C8EB894820842F6A526D814BF9","modified_on":0,"protocol_id":0,"components":[{"id":1054723,"guid":"5BA3DFE70AD34C6CB268F320554F41C7","order_id":1,"type_id":6,"title":"Section","source":{"title":"Data Analysis"}},{"id":1054724,"guid":"B3699081CEE84A90AF841E4E9625C3C3","order_id":1,"type_id":1,"title":"description","source":{"description":"<div class = \"text-blocks\"><div class = \"text-block\">1) \u00a0Count the podocyte numbers (P) and measure the glomerular tuft area (GA) from 100 consecutive cross sections per animal (50 each from thick and thin sections) then calculate the average for each set of 50.<\/div><div class = \"text-block\">\n2) \u00a0Divide the average podocyte number (P) by the avera geglomerular area (GA) to get podocyte number per glomerular area (P\/GA) for both 3 and 9 micron sections.<\/div><div class = \"text-block\">3) \u00a0The difference between the P\/GA of the thick and the P\/GA of the thin sections yields the P\/GA \u0394 which is directly related to the actual difference in sectionthickness (~6 um).<\/div><div class = \"text-block\">\n4) \u00a0Calculate the average glomerular volume per podocyte (GV\/P) by dividing the actual section thickness of 6.3 by the P\/GA\u0394.\n<\/div><div class = \"text-block\">5) \u00a0Determine the glomerular volume by using the Weibel formula\n<\/div><div class = \"text-block\">First, calculate the glomerular radius of both thick and thin sections by assuming circular cross sections using formula<\/div><div class = \"text-block\"><div class = \"justify\" style = \"text-align:center\">radius R = (GA\/\u03c0)\u00bd<\/div><\/div><div class = \"text-block\"><div class = \"justify\" style = \"text-align:center\"><\/div><\/div><div class = \"text-block\"><div class = \"justify\" style = \"text-align:left\"><span>and then calculate the average radius (R<\/span><span style = \"vertical-align:sub;\">av<\/span><span>) that yielded the average maximum radius<\/span><\/div><\/div><div class = \"text-block\"><div class = \"justify\" style = \"text-align:left\"><\/div><\/div><div class = \"text-block\"><div class = \"justify\" style = \"text-align:center\"><span style = \"vertical-align:sub;\">R<\/span><span style = \"vertical-align:sub;\">max<\/span><span> = 4R<\/span><span style = \"vertical-align:sub;\">av<\/span><span>\/\u03c0.<\/span><\/div><\/div><div class = \"text-block\"><div class = \"justify\" style = \"text-align:center\"><\/div><\/div><div class = \"text-block\"><div class = \"justify\" style = \"text-align:left\">Then calculate average glomerular volume as<\/div><\/div><div class = \"text-block\"><div class = \"justify\" style = \"text-align:center\"><span>\nGV = 4\/3\u03c0(R<\/span><span style = \"vertical-align:sub;\">max<\/span><span>)\u00b3<\/span><\/div><\/div><div class = \"text-block\"><div class = \"justify\" style = \"text-align:center\"><\/div><\/div><div class = \"text-block\"><div class = \"justify\" style = \"text-align:left\">Then divide the average glomerular volume by the average volume per podocyte (GV\/P) to get the podocyte number per glomerulus:<\/div><\/div><div class = \"text-block\"><div class = \"justify\" style = \"text-align:left\"><\/div><\/div><div class = \"text-block\"><div class = \"justify\" style = \"text-align:center\">P = GV\/(GV\/P)<\/div><\/div><div class = \"text-block\"><div class = \"justify\" style = \"text-align:center\"><\/div><\/div><div class = \"text-block\"><div class = \"justify\" style = \"text-align:center\"><\/div><\/div><div class = \"text-block\"><div class = \"justify\" style = \"text-align:center\"><\/div><\/div><div class = \"text-block\"><div class = \"justify\" style = \"text-align:center\"><\/div><\/div><\/div>"}}],"cases":[],"data":null,"section":null,"section_color":"#f2f3f6","critical":null,"critical_id":null,"duration":0}],"document":null,"materials":[{"id":203840,"mol_weight":0,"name":"Universal Imaging Metamorph Imaging System ","linfor":"","url":"http:\/\/None","sku":"version 6.1 or later","cas_number":"","rrid":"","public":0,"vendor":{"name":"Molecular Devices","affiliation":null,"affiliations":[],"username":null,"link":"https:\/\/www.moleculardevices.com","image":{"source":"https:\/\/www.protocols.io\/img\/vendors\/placeholder.png","placeholder":"https:\/\/www.protocols.io\/img\/vendors\/placeholder.png"},"badges":[],"research_interests":null,"blocked_by_you":false,"blocked_you":false,"id":319},"can_edit":0,"stats":{"total_protocols":0}},{"id":203841,"mol_weight":0,"name":"Scientific grade digital color CCD camera","linfor":"","url":"http:\/\/None","sku":"","cas_number":"","rrid":"","public":0,"vendor":{"name":"RT SLIDER DIAGNOSTIC","affiliation":null,"affiliations":[],"username":null,"link":"None","image":{"source":"https:\/\/www.protocols.io\/img\/vendors\/placeholder.png","placeholder":"https:\/\/www.protocols.io\/img\/vendors\/placeholder.png"},"badges":[],"research_interests":null,"blocked_by_you":false,"blocked_you":false,"id":553},"can_edit":0,"stats":{"total_protocols":0}},{"id":203842,"mol_weight":0,"name":"Fluorescent Microscope","linfor":"","url":"http:\/\/None","sku":"","cas_number":"","rrid":"","public":0,"vendor":{"name":"Leica DM IRB","affiliation":null,"affiliations":[],"username":null,"link":"https:\/\/www.leica-microsystems.com\/products\/light-microscopes\/p\/leica-dm-il-led\/","image":{"source":"https:\/\/www.protocols.io\/img\/vendors\/placeholder.png","placeholder":"https:\/\/www.protocols.io\/img\/vendors\/placeholder.png"},"badges":[],"research_interests":null,"blocked_by_you":false,"blocked_you":false,"id":554},"can_edit":0,"stats":{"total_protocols":0}}],"description":"<div class = \"text-blocks\"><div class = \"text-block\"><span style = \"font-weight:bold;\">Summary: <\/span><\/div><div class = \"text-block\">This protocol describes a validated protocol used by some DiaComp members to determine podocyte numbers in rodent glomeruli.<\/div><div class = \"text-block\"><span style = \"font-weight:bold;\">Edited by:<\/span><span> Brosius Laboratory<\/span><\/div><div class = \"text-block\"><span style = \"font-weight:bold;\">Diabetic Complication:<\/span><\/div><div style = \"text-align :; float : ;\"><img style = \"\" src = \"https:\/\/s3.amazonaws.com\/pr-journal\/bakkh6.jpg\" \/><\/div><div class = \"text-block\"><span style = \"font-weight:bold;\">Reference: <\/span><\/div><div class = \"text-block\"><span>Sanden SK, Wiggins JE, Goyal M, Riggs LK, and Wiggins RC. Evaluation of a thick and thin section method for estimation of podocyte number, glomerular volume, and glomerular volume per podocyte in rat kidney with Wilms' tumor-1 protein used as a podocyte nuclear marker. <\/span><span style = \"font-style:italic;\">J Am Soc Nephrol 14: 2484-2493, 2003.<\/span><\/div><\/div>","changed_on":1571404834}